# PIE Element Versioning & Tag/ID Contract

## Why this exists

The Custom Elements spec disallows redefining a tag once it has been registered
with `customElements.define`. PIE items can legitimately load multiple versions
of the same package (e.g. preview vs production, item-level override vs
defaults, or side-by-side A/B comparison), so the player encodes the package
version into the tag name itself — e.g. `pie-multiple-choice--version-latest`,
`pie-multiple-choice--version-1-2-3`. See
`packages/players-shared/src/pie/config.ts` (`makeUniqueTags`) for the canonical
encoder and the inline explanation.

Because versioned tag names are the *only* way two versions can coexist at
runtime, they are part of the authored content contract — not opaque author
markup. Stripping, normalizing, or rewriting them silently breaks PIE runtime
element/model binding.

## Rules for tools, sanitizers, and transformers

- Do not strip, trim, or normalize the `--version-<encoded>` suffix on any
  `pie-*` tag name in markup, config, registries, or logs.
- Do not compare a rendered PIE element against its base (non-versioned) tag
  name. Always compare the full tag as it appears after `makeUniqueTags`.
- Authoring-mode variants (`pie-*-config`) are versioned the same way and carry
  the same guarantees; keep them in allow-lists alongside their runtime tags.
- The `id` attribute on `pie-*` elements is a contract key, not content.
  `updateSinglePieElement` in
  `packages/players-shared/src/pie/updates.ts` matches
  `config.models[].id === pieElement.id` by strict equality. Sanitizers,
  transformers, and HTML pre/post-processors must pass `id` through verbatim —
  no prefixing (`user-content-`, `sanitized-`, etc.), no slugging, no casing
  changes, no collapse of repeated hyphens.
- Related contract attributes that must also pass through unchanged:
  `model-id`, `session-id`, `slot`, `data-*`, `aria-*`, `pie-*`, `config-*`,
  `context-*`.

## DOMPurify specifics

- Keep `SANITIZE_DOM: true` for DOM-clobbering defense.
- Keep `SANITIZE_NAMED_PROPS: false` (DOMPurify's default). `true` prefixes
  every `id`/`name` with `user-content-` and silently breaks model lookup.
- Any change that flips `SANITIZE_NAMED_PROPS` must be accompanied by a
  contract-preserving test in
  `packages/players-shared/tests/sanitize-item-markup.test.ts` proving `id`
  round-trips unchanged.
- Use `CUSTOM_ELEMENT_HANDLING.tagNameCheck` / `attributeNameCheck` to allow
  versioned `pie-*` tags and their contract attributes. Do not fall back to
  generic HTML5 allow-lists that would drop unknown tags.

## Classes of changes to reject

- Alias maps that collapse versioned tags back to a base tag for "convenience".
- Regex cleanups that strip `--version-*` or `-config` suffixes before
  comparison or logging (logging is fine; dispatch is not).
- Any sanitizer/transformer that mutates `id`, `model-id`, or `session-id`.
- Any attempt to re-`define` an existing PIE custom element tag; if a new
  version is needed, produce a new versioned tag and update the content.

## Exception policy

The only permitted compatibility surface is the `pie-item` client contract,
per `.cursor/rules/legacy-compatibility-boundaries.mdc`. Exceptions must carry
the inline `pie-item contract compatibility: <reason>` comment and a covering
test.
